T1  - Association of cerebral microbleeds in acute ischemic stroke with high serum levels of vascular endothelial growth factor
A1  - Dassan P.
A1  - Brown M.M.
A1  - Gregoire S.M.
A1  - Keir G.
A1  - Werring D.J.
Y1  - 2012//
N2  - Objective: To determine whether vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGF) levels are associated with the presence of cerebral microbleeds (CMBs) in patients after acute ischemic stroke. Design(s): A cross-sectional study that used blood samples obtained within 24 hours of symptom onset from patients who experienced acute stroke to measure VEGF levels by enzyme immunoassay. A validated CMB rating scale was used to analyze acutely acquired magnetic resonance images, with the rater blind to clinical details and VEGF levels. Setting(s): Accident and Emergency Department at University College Hospital, London, England. Patient(s): Twenty patients who experienced acute ischemic stroke. Main Outcome Measure(s): Presence of CMBs and serum level of VEGF. Result(s): Five of the 20 patients with acute ischemic stroke (25%) had CMBs. The median VEGF level in the CMB group was significantly higher than that in the group without CMBs (P =.003). Conclusion(s): An increase in vascular permeability secondary to a raised VEGF level may have a role in the genesis of CMBs in patients with acute ischemic stroke. ©2012 American Medical Association. All rights reserved.
