T1  - Characteristics of cerebral vascular hemodynamic parameters in young stroke patients
A1  - Guo J.-P.
A1  - Yang Y.-J.
A1  - Cao Y.-F.
A1  - Wang G.-Q.
Y1  - 2005//
N2  - Aim: To analyze and compare the characteristics of cerebral vascular hemodynamic parameters (CVHPs) in young stroke patients. Method(s): Participants under 45 years diagnosed as having stroke with CT or MRI were selected from a cohort population in the northeast and northern China. Risk factors were investigated and CVHPs were checked during base line investigation and an index named accumulative score was estimated according to the CVHPs. Two folds sample of controls without history of stroke were selected from the same population according to age and sex. Defference of CVHPs and its accumulative score between two groups were analyzed. Result(s): Mean score of CVHPs(69.15 +/- 31.42) in young stroke patients was significantly lower than that in controls(87.67 +/- 19.16) (P < 0.01). The mean quantity of blood(Qmean), mean velocity(Vmean), maximal velocity (Vmax), minimum velocity (Vmin) and pressure difference (DP) in young stroke patients were significantly lower than those in controls(P < 0.01). While, peripheral resistance(Rv) in young stroke patients was significantly higher than that in controls(P < 0.05). The obvious changes of indexes in CVHP were DP, Vmin, Qmean, Vmean, Vmax, Rv. Conclusion(s): It seems that the decline in velocity and accumulative score of cerebral vessels function, the increase in Rv are the main characteristics in young stroke patients.
