T1  - Correlation of tumor necrosis factor-alpha and insulin resistance in patients with acute cerebral infarction
A1  - Ma F.-J.
Y1  - 2004//
N2  - Background: Since both tumor necrosis factor-alpha (TNF-alpha) and insulin registance (IR) are the risk factors cerebrovascular diseases, is it possible to alleviate IR and reduce cerebral injury in patients with acute cerebral infarction when TNF-alpha is antagonized? Objective: To explore changes of TNF-alpha and IR and their correlation in acute cerebral infarction patients. Design(s): Case-controlled research based on diagnosis. Settings and participants: Thirty-six healthy people and 48 acute cerebral infarction patients in Baise Municipal People's Hospital, Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, who were accepted from January 2000 to February 2003 and in accord with the diagnosis criterion of the Second National Cerebral Vascular Diseases Conference. Intervention(s): Fasting plasma glucose (FPG), fasting insulin (FINS) and TNF-alpha in every objective were measured by fasting venous blood collection in morning. Oxidase test, radioimmunoassay and the enzyme labeling were adopted respectively in the measurement of FPG, FINS and TNF-alpha. Main Outcome Measure(s): FPG, FINS and TNF-alpha in both acute cerebral infarction group and control group. Result(s): In acute cerebral infarction group, TNF-alpha level was (205 +/- 78) ng/L, FINS(6.18 +/- 1.72) mmol/L, FPG(12.74 +/- 4.33) mU/L, all of them were higher than those in the control group [(76 +/- 18) ng/L, (5.25 +/- 1.28) mmol/L, (7.18 +/- 2.58) mU/L]. Moreover, significant difference could be detected when TNF-alpha level and FINS in acute cerebral infarction group were compared with those in the control group(t = 9.72, 7.33, P < 0.01); TNF-alpha level was positively correlated with FINS(r = 0.53, P < 0.01). Conclusion(s): Both IR and TNF-alpha, which increase in acute cerebral infarction patients and have a close correlation, may participate in the occurrence and development of ischemic cerebral vascular diseases; Therefore, it is possible to alleviate IR and reduce cerebral injury in patients with acute cerebral infarction when TNF-alpha is antagonized.
