T1  - CRP levels and stroke risk
A1  - Curb J.D.
A1  - Belleau G.
A1  - Abbott R.D.
A1  - Rodriguez B.L.
A1  - Sakkinen P.
A1  - Popper J.S.
A1  - Yano K.
A1  - Tracy R.P.
Y1  - 2004//
N2  - In a 20-year follow-up of 259 cases of thromboembolic stroke and 1,348 controls, C-reactive protein (CRP) was found to be positively associated with stroke throughout follow-up. The strongest associations were found at 10 to 15 years after CRP measurement. The association between CRP and thromboembolic stroke was more pronounced in middle-aged men, nonsmokers, and in men without hypertension or diabetes. Additional consideration should be given to the use of CRP as a clinical screening tool to determine increased risk of cardiovascular disease in healthy men.
