T1  - Blood cholesterol level and hemorrhagic stroke. A case control study in Chile
T3  - Niveles de colesterol y accidente vascular hemorragico. Un estudio de casos y controles en Chile
A1  - Diaz V.
A1  - Rodriguez F.
A1  - Cumsille M.A.
Y1  - 1997//
N2  - Objective: To assess whether cholesterol is a risk factor in hemorrhagic stroke (HS) in Chile. Design(s): case-control study. Assuming RR = 2.5, Alpha = 0.05, beta = 0.20 and 15% prevalence of high cholesterol the required sample size is 112 cases and 112 controls. Setting(s): J.J. Aguirre hospital, tertiary universitary hospital. Patient(s): Cases were prospective in patients with HS studied from August 1992 to July 1994. The control group were inpatients from other units: dermatology, urology, surgery etc. coming from the same city. The control group were matched by age and sex to cases. Blood cholesterol level was measured in grs/ml. Other variables studied were diabetes, hypertension, alcohol intake, liver disease and chronic use of medication. The analysis was made with Stata 3.1 statistical package. Chi square, and conditional logistic regression analysis were performed. Result(s): 112 cases and 112 controls were studied. The mean age was 65 years old. 44% were male and 56% were female. The matched analysis of cholesterol showed a mean 181.8 mg/ml (sd = 49.16) for cases and 174.8 mg/ml (sd = 46.6) for control group (t = 1.18, P value = 0.24). Conditional logistic regression analysis show or = 1.00. 95% C.I. 0.99-1.01, P value = 0.24. The hdl or = 1.03, 95 % C.I. 1.00-1.06; the Idl cholesterol or = 1.00, 95% C.I. 0.99-1.01. The cholesterol or adjusted by liver disease, hypertension, chronic use of medication and alcohol intake was 1.0. 95% C.I. 0.99-1.01. No interaction was found between cholesterol and drinker, hypertension and liver disease. Low and high cholesterol levels were not significant risk factor in h.s. Conclusion(s): High and low total cholesterol is not a risk factor for hemorrhagic stroke, controlled by hypertension, liver disease, smoke, alcohol intake and chronic use of medication.
